Given that you have to do this anyway, I wonder if it might be clearer not to use `**kwargs` at all. Instead, data assembly could be
```python
data = {
  "is_high_assurance": high_assurance,
  ...,
  "group_members_visibility": member_visibility if member_visibility != () else None,
  ...
}
data = {k: v for k, v in data.items() if v is not None}
data = {
    k: (data[k] if k in data else existing_data[k])
    for k, v in existing_data.items()
}
```

The main thing I'm looking at is the mix between this "remapping" dict and the somewhat subtle check below of
```python
kwargs.get(option_name) not in (None, ())
```

This makes sense if you remember that a multiple option becomes the empty tuple when omitted. But this is a bit obscure for someone who isn't used to the library.

