Since `my_queue_representation` is a pointer, such a move is incorrect, because it will just copy pointers and result in two queues with the same representation. 
The correct move assignment would be something like:
```
if (my_allocator == other.my_allocator) {
    my_queue_representation = other.my_queue_representation;
    other.my_queue_representation = nullptr;
} else {
    // Deep per-element move, e.g. with assign (again if assign re-allocates everything)
    clear();
    my_queue_representation->assign(*other.my_queue_representation, my_allocator, move_construct_item);
}
```

For move construction/assignment, we should reuse existing move support tests that covers tricky use-cases with equal/unequal allocators. See how it is done for other containers as a reference.

